subject: ENGLISH
text: Read the following passage carefully, and then answer the questions which follow it:

subject: ENGLISH
text: What is the “deception” or “illusion” which Macaulay is here describing?

subject: ENGLISH
text: State in your own words the cause to which he ascribes it.

subject: ENGLISH
text: By what comparison does he illustrate it?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Does the comparison at all points fit the thing to be illustrated? If not, where do you think it fails?

subject: ENGLISH
text: What exactly does Macaulay mean by the last sentence, “But if we...antiquity”?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Do you gather anything from the passage as to Macaulay’s own conception of progress?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Distinguish the following pairs of words: accidental, incidental; dependant, dependent; deprecate, depreciate; ingenious, ingenuous; venal, venial.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Write down two words now in common use which were added to the English vocabulary by each of the following: the mission of St. Augustine; the establishment of the Feudal System; the discovery of America; intercourse with Italy; recent scientific inventions.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Distinguish “epic poems” and “pastoral poems,” and name one example of each, with author. Define “irony,” “a refrain,” “rhetorical question,” and quote or invent one example of each.

subject: ENGLISH
text: When the pilgrims described in Chaucer’s Prologue were riding to Canterbury, into what groups would they naturally fall—i.e., who do you think would ride with whom, having regard to rank and character? Who does Chaucer say rode first, and who last?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Describe any two of Shakespeare’s heroines, so as to bring out the part they take in the action of the play, and the qualities which Shakespeare seems to admire in women.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Illustrate Burns’s sympathy with the working people in their labours, their troubles and their joys, quoting or referring to particular poems. What traces of similar sympathy with the working people have you noticed in Gray and Goldsmith?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Illustrate Wordsworth’s fondness for simple subjects, simple language and simple metres; and compare him in these respects with Keats.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Many Victorian poems take the form of “Dramatic Lyrics,” or “Dramatic Monologues,” in which the poet speaks not in his own person but through an assumed character. Mention five poems of this type by Browning, Tennyson or any other Victorian poet; tell the subject of each, and summarise one of them at some length.

subject: ENGLISH
text: The English Essay has taken various forms. We have reflective or philosophical essays, descriptive essays, historical essays, character sketches, and satirical or humorous essays on manners. Name one example of each of these five kinds, with the author’s name. Describe any one kind more fully, giving several examples of it. Under which head, if any, would you place Lamb’s Dissertation upon Roast Pig?

subject: ENGLISH
text: The events of a novel may be narrated in the first person. Name five examples of this kind of novel by well-known authors, including at least one by Dickens and one by Thackeray. Indicate some of the advantages and disadvantages of the method. Must the narrator always be the hero of the story?
